Clustering Techniques:¶

The Elbow Method:

In the Elbow method, we initialise k-means and use the inertia attribute to identify the sum of squared distances of samples to the nearest cluster centre.</n> As k increases, the sum of squared distance tends to zero. Imagine we set k to its maximum value n (where n is number of samples) each sample will form its own cluster meaning sum of squared distances equals zero.</n> we plot of sum of squared distances for k in the range specified above. If the plot looks like an arm, then the elbow on the arm is optimal k.

Finding the Sum of squared distances:

In [28]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
Sum_of_squared_distances = []
K = range(1,10)
for k in K:
    km = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    km = km.fit(df_sclaed)
    Sum_of_squared_distances.append(km.inertia_)

Ploting the Sum of squared distances::

In [29]:
plt.figure(figsize = (14,10))
plt.plot(K, Sum_of_squared_distances, 'bx-')
plt.xlabel('k')
plt.ylabel('Sum_of_squared_distances')
plt.title('Elbow Method For Optimal k')
plt.show()
As in the above plot we can see the plot have the first arm elbow at 3 hence the optimal number of clusters in our case is 3:¶

Hence we Import KMeans from sklearn and fit it using k=3 clusters on our data set:

In [30]:
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

km = KMeans(
    n_clusters=3, init='random',
    n_init=10, max_iter=300, 
    tol=1e-04, random_state=0
)
km = km.fit(df_sclaed)

Handling outliers of price column:

In [56]:
q1_pr=np.percentile(df['price'],25)
q2_pr=np.percentile(df['price'],75)
iqr_pr=q2_pr-q1_pr
lower_pr=q1_pr - 1.5*iqr_pr
upper_pr=q2_pr + 1.5*iqr_pr
df=df[(df['price']>=lower_pr) & (df['price']<=upper_pr)]

Handling outliers of area Column:

In [57]:
q1_ar=np.percentile(df['area'],25)

upper_ar=q2_ar+1.5*iqr_ar
df=df[(df['area']>=lower_ar) & (df['area']<=upper_ar)]

Modelling: Regression Techniques:

Divide the dataset into training set and testing set (80 percent train and 20 percent test):

Linear Regression Model:

Fit the Linear Regression model on training set and make prediction on testing set:

In [63]:
#Initialize the model
Lr_regressor = LinearRegression()
# Fit the model on training set
Lr_regressor.fit(X_train, y_train)
#  make prediction on testing set
y_pred_lr = Lr_regressor.predict(X_test)

Evaluate the Linear Regression model different evaluation scores:

In [64]:
r2_score_Lr = r2_score(y_pred_lr,y_test)
print("The R2 score is: ",r2_score_Lr)
print("The mean absolute error is: ",mean_absolute_error(y_pred_lr,y_test))
print("The mean squared error is: ",mean_squared_error(y_pred_lr,y_test))
print("The root mean squared error is: ",np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_pred_lr,y_test)))

Separate the Discrete and Continuous features:

In [90]:
discrete_features = [feature for feature in df.columns if df[feature].dtype == 'int64' and len(df[feature].unique())<100]
continuous_features = [feature for feature in df.columns if df[feature].dtype == 'float64' or feature not in discrete_features]
